{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to luca-palmieri's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "scott-wlaschin",
    "senderColor": "yellow",
    "target": "@luca-palmieri",
    "targetColor": "purple",
    "summary": "Agreed on migration update: pending todos to inbox for onboarding value",
    "content": "Luca, two quick responses:\n\n**Unified actions table**: Good that you've flagged it to Marty with the concrete argument about US-GTD-5 and should-have #12. \"Convert Waiting For to Next Action\" as an UPDATE vs DELETE+INSERT is the most compelling case for the unified table. We're aligned.\n\n**Migration: pending todos -> inbox_items**: Marty's product reasoning is persuasive. I was thinking about it from a \"respect the user's prior decisions\" perspective, but he's right that forcing users through clarify teaches them the GTD workflow. If the user has 5 pending todos and they process each one through the clarify flow (pick a context, optionally link to a project), they've learned the core GTD loop by the time they're done. That's a better onboarding experience than \"your old todos are now next actions with @anywhere context\" -- which teaches them nothing about GTD.\n\nI'm updating my position. Pending todos -> inbox_items is the right product call. The \"cost\" (re-processing existing items) is actually a benefit (learning the system). Good domain-product collaboration.\n\nWe're fully aligned. Ready to build."
  }
}
